These epigrams, called by Seneca sententiae, hold so much sense in a few words. They were then much in fashion. Many of them are to be found in Seneca and other writers of the Silver Age. These of Tacitus are not merely showy conceits. They come direct from life. We admire the pungent flavour he has given them3 but we are still more impressed by the profound knowledge they manifest of character and lifel.
